Objective of Assignment 1

The objective of this assignment is to produce a clean, normalized dataset that will be used for the following tasks in this course.

Dataset Overview

-Secretase is a protease known to cleave the CTFs of amyloid-beta precursor protein (APP) at its gamma site. It is also known to cleave other substrates, and has been associated pathways governing cell differentiation. However, we still do not have a full understanding of what -Secretase does to non-proliferating cells (such as neurons).

Dysfunction of lipid metabolism neurons has been linked with Alzheimers Disease. In mouse embryonic fibroblasts (MEFs), -secretase inhibition lowered cellular cholesterol ester levels and reduced endocytosis of the low-density lipoprotein receptor (LDLR). However, No studies were carried out in human neurons, whose cholesterol metabolism is uniquely different from that of glia or peripheral cells.

The authors conducted RNA-seq experiments six biological replicates of induced human neuron cells. There were three treatment protocols: Control, DAPT, and LY411575. Specifically, DAPT and LY411575 treatments pharmaceutically induced chronic inhibition of -secretase. The associated GEO ID for this dataset is GSE206102.

# remove duplicates such that each entrezgene_id has a unique HGNC symbol
unique_hgnc_symbols <- group_by(hgnc_symbols, hgnc_symbol) %>% 
  slice(1) %>%
  group_by(entrezgene_id) %>%

  !(unique_hgnc_symbols$hgnc_symbol == ""), ]

# Merge the table with HGNC symbols
hgnc_tbl <- merge(filtered_tbl, unique_hgnc_symbols, 
                  by.x = "row.names", by.y = "entrezgene_id", all=T)

missing_values <- rownames(hgnc_tbl[is.na(hgnc_tbl$hgnc_symbol), ])
length(missing_values)
[1] 1896

Unfortunately, there were NCBI IDs in which biomaRt was unable to find the corresponding HUGO gene symbol. It seems that the majority of them are either outdated and thus no longer in the current gene set, or they are pseudogenes that do not encode functional proteins. Furthermore, each Entrez ID sometimes corresponds to multiple HGNC symbols, which means some duplicates had to be removed from the dataset in order to have unique row names.

# remove rows that do not have HUGO symbol
hgnc_tbl <- hgnc_tbl[!(is.na(hgnc_tbl$hgnc_symbol)), ]

# Set rownames using HGNC symbols and remove extra columns
rownames(hgnc_tbl) <- hgnc_tbl$hgnc_symbol
filtered_tbl <- hgnc_tbl[, -c(1, ncol(hgnc_tbl))]

We can see that these results are essentially identical to the plot we made earlier. In fact, the normalization factors are all very close to 1, which probably means that the data had already been normalized. Note that the dataset used in this analysis is supposed to be the raw RNA-seq counts. Thus, the original data submitted to GEO had likely been pre-normalized, and NCBI simply performed the processing work to map the data to gene-level counts.

Questions and Answers

What are the control and test conditions of the dataset?
The RNA-seq experiment was conducted over six biological replicates of induced neuronal cells. Tehre were three treatments: control (0.6% DMSO), DAPT(40 uM), and LY411575(2.5 uM). The latter two treatments were used to chronically inhibit -secretase.

Why is the dataset of interest to you?
Alzheimers disease (AD); it is the most common cause of dementia but there havent been any successful therapeutic interventions for this issue. More recently, there have been interesting observations regarding the relationship between dysfunction in lipid metabolism and neuroinflammation in AD. This dataset and its associate paper aims to elucidate this relationship by investigating the direct causal relationship between -secretase, cholesterol, and synapses.

Were there expression values that were not unique for specific genes?
This dataset was originally published at the transcript level using ensembl transcript IDs. As such, I used the the NCBI-generated RNA-seq count data, which had gene-level expression, mapped to unique Entrez Gene IDs. However, when mapping to HUGO symbols, there was an issue with biomaRt returning multiple HGNC IDs for a single Entrez Gene ID, resulting in duplicate genes that had to be removed.

Were there expression values that couldnt be mapped to HUGO symbols?
There were a few genes in the original dataset that likely had outdated Entrez Gene IDs, as biomaRt was unable to locate their HUGO symbol. There was also the aforementioned issue with biomaRt returning multiple HGNC IDs for a single Entrez Gene ID. Overall, after the conversion step from transcript to gene-level expression, 1896 genes were omitted from the dataset.

How many outliers were removed?
I did not remove any sample outliers. As shown by the density and box plots, it seems as though the dataset had already been normalized, as there were no indication of outliers. Hence, no removal of data was performed in this step. The only data that was removed were for low counts; genes were considered expressed when it had >1 count in at least 4 samples.

How did you handle replicates?
The dataset contained six biological replicates, each with three treatments. However, the data NCBI-generated RNA-seq count data only has twelve total samples, with Replicates 1-3 each missing two conditions. Nevertheless, because the samples did not seem to be highly paired between replicates, the analysis was performed on the 12 samples. Thus, the final output data table has 12 columns. Note that when removing genes with low sample counts, I removed entire rows to keep the data consistent.

What is the final coverage of your dataset?
The final dataset coverage is 14244 genes. There are 12 columns (each condition has four total replicates).
